# Project Identity

Project Name: IgnitED Faculty Corner

Description: An AI-powered, syllabus-aligned Learning Management System (LMS) specifically targeting Cambridge & Pearson Edexcel students.

Primary Goal: A working academic prototype demonstrating custom algorithmic logic, role-based routing, and offline/online data integration.

# Tech Stack & Architecture

- Framework: Next.js 15 (Strictly use the App Router: `app/` directory).
- Database & Auth: Supabase (Use `@supabase/supabase-js` or `@supabase/ssr` for server-side auth).
- Styling: Tailwind CSS.
- Component Paradigm: Default to React Server Components (RSC) to minimize client-side javascript. Only use `"use client"` when interactivity or React hooks (useState, useEffect) are strictly required.

# User Roles & Access Control (RBAC)

The system has three distinct roles, managed via Supabase Auth:

1. Student: Takes quizzes, views personalized study paths, tracks progress.
2. Teacher/Faculty: Uploads syllabus nodes, views class analytics.
3. Accountant: Manages offline student payments, prints receipts, and monitors the Risk Flagging dashboard.

Rule: Always verify the user's role via Supabase before rendering protected routes or allowing database mutations.

# Core Development Directives (STRICTLY ENFORCED)

## 1. The "Novelty" & Logic Rule (No Live Generative AI)

Do NOT use external AI APIs (like OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.) at runtime. The application's "AI" value must come from custom algorithms, Rule-Based Expert Systems, and predictive analytics. Write explicit mapping, weighting, and calculation logic directly in Next.js/TypeScript.

## 2. Pre-Generated Data Strategy

To ensure 100% system reliability and zero-latency performance, all MCQ quizzes, topic suggestions, and feedback explanations must be retrieved from pre-generated datasets in the Supabase database. Do not implement real-time text generation.

## 3. Database Schema Blueprint

Assume the following core tables exist in Supabase. Query them accordingly:

- `Users`: id, role (student/teacher/accountant), name
- `Courses`: id, teacher_id, course_name, syllabus_code
- `Enrollments`: id, student_id, course_id, status
- `Payments`: id, student_id, amount, payment_method (cash/online), date
- `Questions`: id, syllabus_code, topic_node, question_text, options (JSONB array), correct_answer, explanation, difficulty_level (1-3)

## 4. Key Algorithmic Features to Implement Manually

- Intelligent Tutoring Routing: When a student finishes a quiz, write logic that calculates their score and queries the `Questions` table for the next logical syllabus node based on their performance (e.g., < 50% routes to Foundation difficulty, > 80% routes to Advanced).
- High Drop-Out Risk Flagging: In the Accountant dashboard, build an algorithm that flags a student by cross-referencing their payment status in the `Payments` table with their recent login/quiz activity.

## 5. UI/UX Standards

- Keep the interface professional, academic, and data-dense.
- Use standard Tailwind utility classes.
- For complex dashboards (like the Accountant ledger or Faculty analytics), break the UI down into small, reusable components.
- Omit complex payment gateway integrations (Stripe, etc.). Treat the `Payments` table as a manual ledger entry system for the Accountant.
